\b \cf3 14.	The Nature of the Virtues\
\pard\pardeftab720\sl360\slmult1
\ls3\ilvl0
\b0 \cf0 Is there any one conception of \'93virtue\'94? Is there anything that unites Jane Austin, St. Paul, Aristotle, and Benjamin Franklin? What about \'91acquisitiveness\'92? Humility? While the virtues are indexed to a society and a practice, there are common elements. A virtue exists in the \'93acceptance of some prior account of... social and moral life...\'94 (186). The first stage invokes \'93practices\'94; the second \'93narrative order of human life\'94 and the third \'93a moral tradition.\'94A practice is a complex social activity with internal goods, like farming, to which standards of excellence (defined by the practice) apply. The virtues are acquired qualities that enable the achievement of the goods of practices. (190). Practices require relationship between those who practice (191). Practices are not 
