\b \cf0 Responses and Reflections\
\pard\pardeftab720\sl360\slmult1
\ls3\ilvl0
\b0 \cf0 The book is divided into two movements. The first, from chps 1-8 tells the story of the problem, the \'93fall.\'94 The second, chps 9-17 tells the story of the solution, \'93redemption,\'94 looking back to go forward. Chp 9 is the cardinal chapter, in my view, the hinge on which the book turns. \
\
Chapter 9 is \'93Nietzsche or Aristotle?\'94 and poses two rivals, the Aristotelian tradition (of virtue) as against the Enlightenment tradition (of morality justified by rationality rather than virtue), where Nietzsche is a sort of Tazmanian devil storming into the rivalry to destroy the Enlightenment tradition \'97 or rather, to unmask is as emotivism: the habit of imposing one\'92s personal feelings on others by force, of manipulation and compulsion. Kant (et. al.,) provide the antecedent, but Nietzsche shoves our noses in a consequent that provides a 
\i reductio ad absurdum 
\i0 for Kant (et. al.). The only remaining option, then, is Aristotle, and virtue. \
\
I find MacIntyre\'92s mythologizing fascinating. He is telling stories. The key to this book is the narrative unity of the human life chapter, where he says human beings are story-tellers. \
